[h1]Working with Canvas[/h1]

The Canvas element can be transformed. As an example, a text is written on the canvas at the coordinates (10, 30). [code format="raw" codeId="60"]ctx.[b]font[/b]="bold 22px Tahoma";
ctx.[b]textAlign[/b]="start";
ctx.[b]fillText[/b]("start", 10, 30);[/code]
[b]Result:[/b] [img id="2559" width="100%"]
The [b]translate(x,y)[/b] method is used to move the Canvas.
x indicates how far to move the grid horizontally, and y indicates how far to move the grid vertically. [code format="raw" codeId="61"]ctx.[b]translate[/b](100, 150);
ctx.fillText("after translate", 10, 30);[/code]
In this example, the canvas is moved 100px to the right, and 150px down.
[b]Result:[/b] [img id="2560" width="100%"]

[h1]The rotate() Method[/h1]

The [b]rotate()[/b] method is used to rotate the HTML5 Canvas. The value must be in radians, not degrees.

Here is an example that draws the same rectangle before and after rotation is set: [code format="raw" codeId="62"]ctx.fillStyle = "#FF0000";
ctx.fillRect(10,10, 100, 100);

ctx.[b]rotate[/b]( (Math.PI / 180) * 25);  //rotate 25 degrees.

ctx.fillStyle = "#0000FF";
ctx.fillRect(10,10, 100, 100);[/code]
[img id="2561" width="100%"]

[h1]The scale() Method[/h1]

The [b]scale() [/b]method scales the current drawing. It takes two parameters:
 - The number of times by which the image should be scaled in the X-direction.
 - The number of times by which the image should be scaled in the Y-direction. [code format="raw" codeId="63"]var canvas = document.getElementById('canvas1');
ctx =canvas.getContext('2d');
ctx.font="bold 22px Tahoma";
ctx.textAlign="start";
ctx.fillText("start", 10, 30);
ctx.translate(100, 150);
ctx.fillText("after translate", 0, 0);
ctx.rotate(1);
ctx.fillText("after rotate", 0, 0);
ctx.[b]scale(1.5, 4)[/b];
ctx.fillText("after scale", 0,20);[/code]
This will scale the canvas 1.5 times in the X-direction, and 4 times in Y-direction: [img id="2562" width="100%"]
